\begin{align*}
\boxed{[0, \infty)}
\end{align*}

Ah, polynomial multiplication! A classic.  To expand $(2x^5 + 3x^2)(x^4 - 4x^2 + 3x - 8)$, we distribute each term of the first polynomial to every term of the second:

\begin{align*}
(2x^5 + 3x^2)(x^4 - 4x^2 + 3x - 8) &= 2x^5(x^4 - 4x^2 + 3x - 8) + 3x^2(x^4 - 4x^2 + 3x - 8) \\
&= 2x^9 - 8x^7 + 6x^6 - 16x^5 + 3x^6 - 12x^4 + 9x^3 - 24x^2 \\
&= 2x^9 - 8x^7 + 9x^6 - 16x^5 - 12x^4 + 9x^3 - 24x^2 
\end{align*}

When multiplying radicals with the same index, we can combine them by multiplying the radicands.  This gives us:

√[3]{12} × √[3]{20} × √[3]{15} × √[3]{60} = √[3]{12 × 20 × 15 × 60}

Now, let's simplify inside the radical:

√[3]{12 × 20 × 15 × 60} = √[3]{216000}

Finally, find the cube root of 216000:

√[3]{216000} = 60

