As an expert in cylindrical volume calculations, I can tell you that the number of new containers Sean needs depends on the ratio of their volumes.  Since the new containers are twice the radius but the same height, their volume is four times larger (radius is squared in the volume formula).

Therefore, Sean can fit the contents of four small containers into each large container. With 12 small containers, he'll only need 12 / 4 = 3 large containers. 


\begin{center}
$\boxed{3}$
